Methylene blue, also known as methylthioninium chloride, is a synthetic compound with diverse applications across industries, including pharmaceuticals, aquaculture, and biological staining. Initially developed in 1876 as an aniline-based dye for the textile industry, methylene blue has evolved into a vital compound in medicine, particularly in the treatment of methemoglobinemia, malaria, and other medical conditions. Additionally, it is widely utilized as a staining agent in microbiology and histology.

